You need two things: a **navigation guard** in `AppShell` and **`BackButtonBehavior`** on the page.

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage`

```xml
<!-- EditProductPage.xaml -->
<ContentPage ...>
    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <!-- form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

```csharp
// In your ViewModel
[RelayCommand]
async Task Cancel()
{
    if (HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard changes and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");
        if (!discard) return;
    }
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

### 2. Guard the hardware/gesture back (Android swipe, system back)

The custom button handles tap, but the system back button and swipe gestures bypass it. Override `OnNavigating` in `AppShell` to catch those:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    // Only intercept back-navigation (Pop)
    if (args.Source != ShellNavigationSource.Pop)
        return;

    // Check if the current page is EditProductPage
    if (Shell.Current.CurrentPage is not EditProductPage page)
        return;

    // Check for unsaved changes via the ViewModel
    if (page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        // Must get deferral BEFORE any await
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard changes and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

### Key points

- **`GetDeferral()`** — must be called *before* any `await`; without it, async guards race and navigation completes before your dialog resolves.
- **`deferral.Complete()`** — always call this (even after cancel) to release the navigation pipeline.
- **`BackButtonBehavior.Command`** replaces the default back-arrow behavior entirely, so the `OnNavigating` guard only fires for system/gesture back — no double-prompt.
